"# Hotspot Handbook\n"
"\n"
"## Hotspot review policies, instructions, and standards\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: Introduction.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Thank you for volunteering to help review and manage eBird hotspots. This "
"document describes the purpose of hotspots, how to review and approve "
"requests for new hotspots, and how to rename, relocate, merge and manage the "
"hierarchy of existing hotspots."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Hotspots allow birders to submit data to common locations. The idea is to "
"aggregate data from these hotspots and provide output that is useful to "
"birders wishing to learn more about birds and their distribution. With "
"pooled data from multiple observers, hotspots become a valuable tool for "
"finding out when and where to see birds in your area and elsewhere. All "
"eBird hotspots appear in the eBird Hotspot Explorer (<http://ebird.org/ebird/"
"hotspots>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:8
msgid ""
"It is important to remember that **data collected at FINE resolutions are "
"much more valuable than data aggregated over very large areas**. For this "
"reason, we try to include sub-hotpots (see [Hotspot Definitions and "
"Hierarchy](HotspotDefinitions.qmd)) in order to incentivize birders towards "
"birding across shorter distances and using hotspots that are closely tied to "
"their location on the ground.  So, while we do have a hotspot for Rocky "
"Mountain NP (Larimer Co), we also have many hotspots for locations within "
"Rocky Mountain NP, for example [Rocky Mountain NP--Endovalley Picnic Area]"
"(https://ebird.org/hotspot/L6136876)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Introduction.qmd:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "**What is an eBird Hotspot?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:12
msgid ""
"eBird hotspots are primarily useful as a way of aggregating data from "
"multiple observers under a single location. This simplifies data entry by "
"providing curated, properly-sited, and sensibly-named locations that "
"represent a given birding site and aggregates similar birding effort under a "
"single location. Because Hotspots can significantly impact the data entry "
"process—influencing where birders choose to go both within a site and within "
"a region—they should be created, named, and positioned to clearly and "
"intuitively reflect the area they cover. Most hotspots should be publicly "
"accessible, but see [Restricted Access locations]"
"(RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd) section below. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:14
msgid ""
"During data entry in eBird mobile, users that start a checklist will get a "
"list of recommended hotspots nearby. Submitted data can then easily be "
"explored on eBird hotspot pages on the web, which includes tools like bar "
"charts, iconic birds, illustrated checklists, photo galleries, recent "
"visits, and of course an official list of species for the site. Hotspot "
"summary pages can be really useful for landowners or land managers as a "
"quick way to understand birds on the property, but see below section on "
"[Hotspot Definitions and Hierarchy](HotspotDefinitions.qmd) and note that "
"hotspots should not be merged just to improve data summaries (data can be "
"combined for data summaries in other ways!). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:16
msgid ""
"Please think of eBird hotspots as **curated sites visited repeatedly by the "
"eBird community**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:18
msgid ""
"eBird hotspots are **not** necessarily superlative birding locations; they "
"can be designated for high species diversity, presence of one or several "
"specialty species, a regularly birded location that is publicly accessible, "
"or almost anywhere in which it is desirable to aggregate data from multiple "
"eBirders in a single point. Sometimes hotspots represent frequently visited "
"tourist sites where birders are likely to keep an eBird checklist, "
"especially if visiting from abroad and experiencing new life birds. In "
"certain cases, eBird hotspots are established for scientific surveys. Some "
"examples of hotspots that may not be obvious include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Introduction.qmd:20
msgid ""
"[Piazza San Pietro](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1107515) \\[urban, paved "
"plaza, and popular tourist site\\]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Introduction.qmd:22
msgid ""
"[Sap Anan--PTT gas station on Hwy. 4 (southbound)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L6368496) \\[gas station and rest area along route popular with birders; not "
"particularly good for birds but a spot many birders will stretch their legs "
"and take a break\\]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Introduction.qmd:24
msgid ""
"[Detroit Metro Airport (restricted access)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L299938) \\[this and many airports are appropriate hotspots, even when "
"viewing from the terminals only; many traveling birders will enter lists and "
"airports do provide grassland habitat that may attract specialty species\\]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Introduction.qmd:25
#, no-wrap
msgid "**What is not an eBird hotspot?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Introduction.qmd:28
msgid "Examples of sites that should not be hotspots include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Introduction.qmd:30
msgid "Personal yards and other private property"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Introduction.qmd:32
msgid "Personal walking routes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Introduction.qmd:34
msgid ""
"Property that is visited only by one person or by small numbers of people "
"with permission only"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Introduction.qmd:35
msgid ""
"Random interesting observations unlikely to be repeated (e.g., along a major "
"road or at an unremarkable area of urban or suburban habitat)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:2
msgid ""
"This section describes how to sign in to the Hotspot Review Tools, view "
"hotspot suggestions in your area, open and review a hotspot suggestion, and "
"then accept (or reject) a hotspot. Chrome, Safari, and Mozilla Firefox "
"browsers are all fully supported; other browsers may not work as well. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: Overview.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Log in to the eBird Hotspot Review Tools (<https://ebird.org/admin/"
"hotspots.htm>) using your standard eBird credentials. If you are logged in "
"to a different account, you will not be able to edit hotspots. We recommend "
"bookmarking this page."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: Overview.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Make sure that you are in the Hotspots tab at the top left of the screen "
"(see below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:8
msgid "![](images/paste-3.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:10
#, no-wrap
msgid "**View and Sort Pending Hotspot Suggestions**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:12
msgid ""
"The list of hotspots waiting for evaluation in your review region is visible "
"on the default page of the Hotspot Review Tools: <https://ebird.org/admin/"
"hotspots.htm>. You can sort this page by any of the columns; just click the "
"header (e.g., Name, Country), and you’ll be all set. You can also search the "
"list of pending hotspots by using Command+F on a Mac, or Ctrl+F on a PC. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:14
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Open and Review Hotspot Suggestions**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:16
msgid "![](images/paste-4.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:18
msgid ""
"It is important to know that **clicking “Review” immediately accepts a given "
"hotspot**, and then allows editing (changing name, location, or merging) to "
"improve it as needed. If it is [not an appropriate hotspot]"
"(ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd), there are just two clicks required: “Review” and "
"then “Revert to personal location” and then the hotspot request is removed "
"and the hotspot will not be created. This tentative acceptance makes the "
"process efficient, but it is important to understand. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Overview.qmd:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** For more details and explanations on editing hotspots (including deleting a hotspot and reverting a hotspot to a personal location) refer to the “[Editing Existing Hotspots](EditingExistingHotspots.qmd)” section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**To Accept or Not Accept**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Many hotspots cannot be immediately accepted, or accepted at all. Here are "
"some common situations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd:6
msgid ""
"If a user recommends a hotspot that clearly does not meet the criteria for a "
"shared hotspot (such as \"My Backyard\" or just the user’s name such as "
"\"Steve Jones\"), go ahead and resolve the recommendation by clicking "
"“Review” and then “Revert to Personal Location.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd:8
msgid ""
"Be conscious of duplicate suggestions. Sometimes, a user will recommend a "
"hotspot similar to one that already exists. In that case, don’t accept the "
"Hotspot. Consider merging the suggested hotspot. If the suggestion is an "
"improvement over the existing hotspot, merge the suggestion, then move or "
"rename the existing hotspot."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd:10
msgid ""
"Occasionally, a hotspot will be recommended that has no data associated with "
"it. In these cases the hotspot editing screen will have a delete option next "
"to the hotspot name. This only appears for locations with no data associated "
"with them (i.e., you cannot delete a location that has associated data). In "
"these cases, feel free to delete the location if it is not a worthy hotspot. "
"Some hotspots might appear to have no data, but they won’t have the deletion "
"option. This is most likely because they have hidden checklists or only have "
"sensitive, rare and/or unaccepted species, but they still have data, so "
"deletion isn’t an option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd:12
msgid ""
"If you just can't figure out what the user's intent was, send an email to "
"find out. When in doubt, revert to a personal location. This is always the "
"safest option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd:14
msgid ""
"\\ Hotspot organization and hierarchy can be managed in additional ways, so "
"decisions to accept new hotspots should focus on their potential benefit to "
"data entry and aggregation. Read the sections on [What is a Hotspot?]"
"(Introduction.qmd#what-is-an-ebird-hotspot) and [Hotspot Naming]"
"(HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd) for guidance on special circumstances such as sub-"
"hotspots or list-building parent hotspots."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**New Hotspot Evaluation**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:4
msgid ""
"**Check for duplicates**—Select the Merge option. This does not merge the "
"hotspot yet, but loads other hotspots in the area so that you can check if "
"the hotspot you just accepted already exists nearby with the same or a "
"similar name. If it does already exist, merge the new location with the "
"existing hotspot. If it does not already exist, proceed with the next steps. "
"Caution: Make sure the new hotspot is really a duplicate before merging. "
"Merging cannot be reversed! \\*\\*NOTE: When merging with an existing "
"hotspot if you do not select Delete after merging, the new hotspot will "
"persist with no data.**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:6
msgid ""
"**Consider if the hotspot is acceptable**—see “[To Accept or Not Accept]"
"(ToAcceptorNotAccept.qmd)”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3.  '
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:8
msgid ""
"**Check that the name matches eBird naming protocols** (see [Part IV]"
"(Part4.qmd)). If necessary, click **Rename** and rename the hotspot."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4.  '
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:10
msgid ""
"**Confirm location—**If you need to move the new hotspot, select the "
"**Move** option, click the new location on the map, and then click **Move** "
"again. \\*\\***NOTE:** This step should be last, because it automatically "
"closes the hotspot editing window."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5.  '
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:12
msgid ""
"**Consider hotspot hierarchy–if the new hotspot is best understood as a "
"subhotspot within a group that already exists, go to the parent hotspot "
"Admin tools and add the new one as a subhotspot. Similarly, for new parent "
"hotspots, add any subhotspots to them.**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:14
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Finito! You’re done, and another hotspot has joined the system!!!** Return to the Hotspot Review Tools, and the suggestion no longer appears in the unreviewed hotspots page. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:17
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**\\\n"
"\\*\\*NOTE**: If you change your mind on acceptance or need to revisit the hotspot, see the [Viewing Reviewed Hotspots](ViewingReviewedHotspots.qmd) section below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Allow time for the database to update**. The hotspot page will be viewable with the correct link immediately, and checklists will correctly link to it, but some of the exploration tools in the Hotspot Explorer (including the map) update once every \\~24 hours. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:23
msgid ""
"If someone suggests the same Hotspot more than once, you will need to wait "
"until the next day to review the others if you want to merge them. Likewise, "
"if two users suggest the same location, review and accept one, then wait "
"until the next day to review and merge the other.\\ \\ **Pro Tip:** If you "
"accidentally accept two duplicate hotspots on the same day, add “(Merge)” to "
"the name of one so you can easily find and correct it later. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NewHotspotEvaluation.qmd:24
msgid ""
"Submit Data and Hotspot editing maps are nearly live queries (every two "
"hours), so the hotspot lists here will be almost current."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ViewingReviewedHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Viewing Reviewed Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ViewingReviewedHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"At the top right of the Hotspot Review Tools page, there is a “Show "
"Reviewed” button. Click to see list of all the hotspots that have already "
"been reviewed in your review region except for merged . This page shows who "
"accepted or didn’t accept the hotspot and when."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ViewingReviewedHotspots.qmd:6
msgid "![](images/paste-5.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ViewingReviewedHotspots.qmd:8
msgid ""
"All columns on this page are sortable if you click on the header—with the "
"right two being most important. The “Reviewed On” column lets you view by "
"time of review, and “View in eBird” takes you to the Edit hotspot screen "
"where you can revisit hotspot decisions that have already been made."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ViewingReviewedHotspots.qmd:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Re-review** will re-Accept a hotspot that was previously marked Not Accepted.  giving you the option to review (rename, merge, or move) it again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Editing Existing Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Existing hotspots can be renamed, moved, merged, deleted, and reverted to "
"personal locations using the Hotspot Explorer in eBird. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:6
msgid "Sign in to eBird."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:8
msgid "Navigate to the hotspot you wish to edit. Easy ways to do that include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    1.  '
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:10
msgid "Click the hotspot name from an eBird checklist."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    2.  '
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:12
msgid "Find it on the eBird Hotspot map (https://ebird.org/hotspots). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    3.  '
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:14
msgid ""
"Select it from the list of hotspots on a region page (top 100 hotspots only)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3.  '
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:17
msgid ""
"From the Hotspot map: Click the **Edit** link to open the Edit Location page."
"\\ From an individual Hotspot page: Tap **Admin** from the navigation sidebar"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:19
msgid "![](images/paste-6.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:21
msgid "![](images/paste-7.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Rename**—To change the hotspot name, select the **Rename** option, type the new name, and click **Rename**. (See [Part IV: Standards and Naming Conventions for eBird Hotspots](Part4.qmd))\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:26
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**\\\n"
"Manage Sub-Hotspots**—[see Hotspot Groups](Part3.qmd)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Move—**To move the hotspot, select the **Move** option, click on the map to plot the new location, and then click **Move** again. (See [Plotting Hotspots](PlottingHotspots.qmd)) **NOTE:** If you know the coordinates of the new location, enter them in the **Zoom to:** box, press the **\\<Enter\\>** key, and then click **Move**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Merge—**See [Merging Hotspots](MergingHotspots.qmd). The option to merge only appears if a Hotspot has at least one eBird checklist associated with it. To merge two hotspots, select the **Merge** option. The map will display the surrounding hotspots as red pins, and the hotspot you’re working with will be shown as an orange pin with a plus sign. Click the hotspot that you want to merge your current hotspot *INTO*, select the **Delete after merging** check box, and then click **Merge**. Be careful! Merging cannot be undone.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "**NOTE:** If you do not select Delete after merging, the old hotspot will persist with no data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Revert to Personal Location—**Reverts a hotspot to a personal location. If the personal location that is created is shared among several observers, the one with the oldest checklist (i.e., the first checklist ever submitted for the site, not the oldest observation date) will become the \"owner\" of the location and is  responsible for any moves, renaming, or merging of this location, and also is the only one able to recommend it again as a hotspot. **NOTE:** You can still find these in the “Reviewed” tab if you want to reverse your decision.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:36
msgid "![](images/paste-8.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:38
msgid ""
"Above: This warning appears if you attempt to Revert any hotspot that is "
"actively part of a Hotspot Group. Go to the Hotspot Admin page for the "
"[parent hotspot](https://team-ebird.github.io/eBird_Hotspot_Manual/"
"Part3.html) and remove the hotspot from the group. It can then be reverted "
"to a personal location."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: EditingExistingHotspots.qmd:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Delete—**You will only see the option to delete a hotspot if it has no eBird checklists associated with it. In this case, a blue **delete** option appears next to the name. There is little point in maintaining hotspots with no data, unless you are confident they will be useful in the future. Please delete these if you deem it appropriate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: PlottingHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Plotting Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: PlottingHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Exactly where to plot a hotspot is something of a judgment call. These "
"general rules should be followed:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: PlottingHotspots.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Plot the hotspot in a place that is a good representation of where most "
"birding takes place. If a 400 hectare park has a well-used hiking trail in "
"the western third and a patch of forest with no trails that takes up the "
"eastern two-thirds, plot the hotspot closer to the heavily used western end, "
"not in the middle or eastern portion."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: PlottingHotspots.qmd:8
msgid ""
"Plot the hotspot in a place that navigation apps (e.g., Google Maps, Waze) "
"will accurately direct a birder to the location. For example, placing a "
"hotspot in the middle of the woods that would direct Google Maps to an "
"access point that does not exist, instead of the primary parking area, is "
"not ideal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3.  '
#: PlottingHotspots.qmd:9
msgid ""
"For general areas (AKA “[list-building parent hotspots](List-"
"buildingParentHotspots.qmd)”),  plot them in a central location relative to "
"their constituent sub-hotspots, but make sure they are sufficiently "
"separated from other hotspots to stand out from the rest. This helps "
"identify the list-building parent hotspots on a map. For example, if there "
"are a cluster of hotspots around a wildlife drive in a refuge, place the "
"list-building parent hotspot towards the refuge’s center, sufficiently away "
"from the other hotspots so that users can easily find it and select it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: MergingHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Merging Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: MergingHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"When you merge two hotspots, the data from two locations is combined into a "
"single hotspot. For example, if hotspot A is plotted correctly, but hotspot "
"B has a similar name and is plotted nearby (and is a clear duplicate), you "
"should merge hotspot B \\*into\\* hotspot A. In almost all cases, you should "
"also select the \"Delete after merging” check box so that the hotspot you "
"merged the data from (in this case hotspot B) will be deleted. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: MergingHotspots.qmd:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Please be VERY careful when merging and deleting hotspots as this action cannot be reversed. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: MergingHotspots.qmd:8
msgid ""
"ALWAYS KEEP MORE REFINED LOCATIONS SEPARATE FROM THE MAIN LOCATION \\[e.g., "
"DO NOT MERGE “Rocky Mountain NP--Endovalley Campground” into the “Rocky "
"Mountain NP (Larimer Co)” hotspot\\]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: MergingHotspots.qmd:10
msgid "![](images/paste-9.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: MergingHotspots.qmd:11
msgid ""
"Above: This warning appears if you attempt to Merge any hotspot that is "
"actively part of a Hotspot Group. Go to the Hotspot Admin page for the "
"parent hotspot and remove the hotspot from the group. It can then be "
"reverted to a personal location."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Content Permissions**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:4
msgid ""
"**All eBirders:** Can suggest new content or changes to existing content"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:6
msgid ""
"**eBird Reviewers AND eBirders with 100+ complete checklists in the previous "
"calendar year:** Content suggestions are automatically approved (except for "
"sites with Auto-approval turned “Off”)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:8
msgid ""
"**Accounts with Content Editing permissions:** All of the above, plus the "
"ability to:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:10
msgid "Approve/Decline pending content suggestions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:12
msgid "View content suggestion history"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:14
msgid "Directly edit About pages (including adding links)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:16
msgid "Disable suggestion Auto-approval on individual hotspots"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:18
msgid "**eBird Hotspot Editors:** All of the above, plus:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:20
msgid "Approve new Hotspots"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:22
