msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:24
msgid "Create or edit Hotspot Groups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:26
msgid ""
"Grant content editing permissions (to any subregion(s) within their assigned "
"hotspot region)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:28
msgid ""
"Additional content editing permissions can be granted to accounts to assist "
"with content management. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ContentPermissions.qmd:29
msgid "![](images/paste-25.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Assigning Content Editing Permissions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:4
msgid ""
"eBird Hotspot Editors go to <https://review.ebird.org/review/hotspots/manage-"
"access> OR navigate to any Hotspot in your assigned region and tap About \\> "
"Review \\> Manage Access.  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:6
msgid ""
"You will need to know the eBird User ID of the account—this is different "
"than their username. User IDs are formatted as USER123456"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:8
msgid "If you are not sure of the person’s User ID: "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:10
msgid "Go to [search.macaulaylibrary.org](http://search.macaulaylibrary.org) "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:12
msgid ""
"Tap Contributor, type their name\\*, and tap when it appears in the dropdown"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3.  '
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:14
msgid ""
"Their UserID will be displayed in the resulting webpage address (e.g., "
"<https://search.macaulaylibrary.org/catalog?userId=USER123456>) "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:16
msgid ""
"\\* If multiple accounts share the same name, you may need to ask the "
"account holder to perform these steps, repeating Step 2 as necessary  until "
"the correct account is selected (process of elimination). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AssigningContentEditingPermissions.qmd:17
msgid ""
"If you still can’t figure out the name, any eBird observation reviewer can "
"see this by clicking on the user’s name from the Review Tools."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: HotspotContent.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Hotspot Content**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotContent.qmd:4
msgid ""
"For instructions on About This Hotspot text sections and Features, visit the "
"eBird help center: [eBird Hotspot About Pages](https://support.ebird.org/en/"
"support/solutions/articles/48001281732)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotContent.qmd:6
msgid "A note to editors on using AI to generate Hotspot content**:**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotContent.qmd:8
msgid ""
"AI can be a helpful tool to organize, format, and copyedit About content. "
"However, AI has its limitations and should always be read and human-verified "
"before publishing. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotContent.qmd:10
msgid ""
"When considering using AI for Hotspot content, we first strongly recommend "
"generating content for the Hotspots that you are the MOST familiar with. "
"Review the content, noting any inaccuracies. If possible, ask the AI for its "
"sources and consult them directly to understand where content is obtained "
"and how accurately it has been adapted. Repeat until you feel you have a "
"good sense of the AI tool’s performance. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: HotspotContent.qmd:12
msgid "Always read the content word-for-word "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: HotspotContent.qmd:14
msgid ""
"If you are not familiar with a site, try to find someone who is familiar "
"with it to review its content (consider: if the AI output is wrong, how will "
"you know?) "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: HotspotContent.qmd:16
msgid ""
"Double-check AI-generated hours, dates, posted fees, and anything involving "
"numbers (AI is known to hallucinate!)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotContent.qmd:18
msgid ""
"\\ A note on Accessibility: Humans and AI alike are encouraged to avoid "
"subjective assessments of accessibility such as “Wheelchair friendly” or "
"“Easily accessible”. Instead of these vague phrases, provide detailed "
"information about the physical description of the birding location. Include "
"details such as trail surfaces, gradient/slope, safety features, degree of "
"maintenance, crowd and noise levels, etc. **Consider using the [Birdability]"
"(https://www.birdability.org/) Site Review Checklist to guide your "
"description.** Aim to help others make an assessment for themselves whether "
"the site is accessible to them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Managing Languages**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:5
msgid "\\ Which language is displayed first?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:7
msgid ""
"If a user has the eBird website or their browser set to a particular "
"language, we first display About content in that language, if available."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:9
msgid ""
"If no content is available in the user's browser/web language, we then try "
"to display content in the regional default language, if applicable. (e.g., "
"For eBird Japan, the regional default language is Japanese. For eBird Chile, "
"the regional default language is Spanish)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3.  '
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:11
msgid ""
"If there is no content in either the user's preferred language or the "
"regional default language, we will show ANY available content.\\* "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4.  '
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:13
msgid ""
"Finally, if there is no content at all, we display a message \"Nothing added "
"yet for this hotspot. Suggest content\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5.  '
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:15
msgid ""
"Note that bird names that use the species tags will always display for "
"logged-in users according to the user’s [common name preferences](https://"
"ebird.org/prefs), regardless of the other language settings."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\* Whenever multiple languages are available, go to Edit Content \\> Manage Languages to choose which language is displayed first. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:19
msgid "![](images/paste-10.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ManagingLanguages.qmd:20
#, no-wrap
msgid "**If a language has no content**: Go to Edit Content \\> Manage Languages to delete it. (Be careful, this will also delete any existing content!)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Links.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Links**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Links.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Only Hotspot Editors and accounts with content editing permissions can add "
"and manage Hotspot About links. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Links.qmd:6
msgid ""
"There can only be one “Official Website” link. This link will be more "
"prominently highlighted at the top of the hotspot content. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Links.qmd:8
msgid ""
"You can have unlimited Hotspot links. Link Titles appear the same across all "
"languages. We recommend using a short, descriptive title of the page in its "
"default language. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Links.qmd:9
msgid "![](images/paste-11.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ContentEditHistory.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Content Edit History**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ContentEditHistory.qmd:4
msgid "Only users with content editing permissions can see this panel."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ContentEditHistory.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Content Edit History shows the last 100 edits made to this hotspot's About "
"content sections, including who made the change and when. Changes to "
"Features and Links are not reflected here. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ContentEditHistory.qmd:7
msgid ""
"Details show comparison with the version before it—added text is highlighted "
"in green and removed text in red. Uncheck \"Compare with previous version\" "
"on any entry to view the content without highlights."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Auto-Approval.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Auto-Approval**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Auto-Approval.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "eBird volunteers and anyone with \\>100 complete eBird checklists in the previous year will have their suggestions automatically approved, meaning their edits will appear on the public About page immediately upon submission. Automatically approved changes will be tracked in the Content Edit History and [Reviewed Content Suggestions](Reviewedsuggestions.qmd) (below) and Content Editors can always adjust or reverse changes by copying text from an earlier version of the page and pasting it back into the relevant sections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Reviewingcontentsuggestions.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Reviewing Content Suggestions**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Reviewingcontentsuggestions.qmd:4
msgid ""
"eBird Hotspot Editors and anyone with content editing permissions for a "
"hotspot can review suggestions made by eBirders without these permissions. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Reviewingcontentsuggestions.qmd:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "**To review content**, tap the “Review” button on any Hotspot About page in your assigned region OR\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Reviewingcontentsuggestions.qmd:7
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Bookmark <https://review.ebird.org/review/hotspots/content-suggestions>** for quick access to your entire suggestion queue\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Pending Suggestions**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:4
#, no-wrap
msgid "**For pending (un-reviewed) suggestions**, tap “Details” to see what changed\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:6
msgid "**Accept:** anything in GREEN will be added to the Hotspot About page"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:8
msgid ""
"**Decline: anything in RED will be removed from the Hotspot About page**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:10
msgid "**Close: hide details without acting on them**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:12
msgid ""
"WARNING: “Details” shows how the suggested changes will impact the current "
"About page. If the underlying About content has changed since the suggestion "
"was made, the comparison shows what will actually change (not necessarily "
"what the suggester saw at the time of their revisions). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:14
msgid ""
"If you Accept more recent pending suggestions, earlier pending suggestions "
"may no longer apply (i.e., the text being changed may no longer exist on the "
"page) We recommend quickly scanning the Details of all pending suggestions "
"for a single hotspot before Accepting any of them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "**(!)** eBird Hotspot Editors can see the personal account details for the eBirder who made the suggestion, including contact details. People with content editing permissions can only see the name of the person who made the suggestion, with a link to their eBird profile if public. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:18
msgid "![](images/paste-12.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Pendingsuggestions.qmd:19
msgid ""
"Switch between suggestions for a single hotspot and all hotspots. You can "
"also filter pending suggestions by language."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Reviewedsuggestions.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Reviewed Suggestions**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Reviewedsuggestions.qmd:4
msgid ""
"After tapping Accept or Decline, the suggestion will move to the “Reviewed” "
"tab. The Details here will show you who made the suggestion and when, "
"whether it was Accepted or Declined, and who reviewed it. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Reviewedsuggestions.qmd:6
msgid "![](images/paste-13.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Reviewedsuggestions.qmd:8
#, no-wrap
msgid "**eBird Hotspot Administrator**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Reviewedsuggestions.qmd:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "Any suggestion accepted by “eBird Hotspot Administrator” is an Auto-approved suggestion—i.e., the person who made the suggestion is either an eBird Reviewer/Hotspot Editor OR they submitted \\>100+ complete eBird checklists in the previous calendar year.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: HotspotcontentFAQs.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Hotspot Content FAQs**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: HotspotcontentFAQs.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Can I undo or revert an About page back to an earlier version?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotcontentFAQs.qmd:5
msgid ""
"While it is not possible to undo or reverse changes once accepted, you can "
"always restore a previous version of About content by copy-pasting text from "
"the [Content Edit History](ContentEditHistory.qmd) panel. (Uncheck the "
"“Compare with previous version” box so that you can copy the text without "
"highlighted changes.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**What is a Hotspot Group?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:4
msgid ""
"A **Hotspot Group** consists of two or more hotspots that are part of the "
"same continuous geographical area."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Hotspot Groups organize multiple hotspots within a larger area. For example, "
"a state park or wildlife refuge might contain separate eBird hotspots for "
"individual trails, viewpoints, or other popular birding spots. These "
"hotspots would collectively form a hotspot group under a single overview "
"page (AKA [parent hotspot](ParentHotspots.qmd)) that refers to the entire "
"area."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:8
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Each hotspot can only belong to one group at a time** due to technical requirements related to [data aggregation](DataAggregation.qmd).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:10
msgid ""
"Hotspots should only be grouped if they occupy the same general area—"
"typically this area has clearly defined boundaries and/or is under a single "
"jurisdiction or management entity (i.e., sites should generally form a "
"contiguous cluster). Birders often may visit multiple hotspots within this "
"boundary on a single visit (ideally, but not always, keeping separate "
"checklists). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "**What is NOT a hotspot group?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:14
msgid "The following should NOT be made into hotspot groups:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:16
msgid ""
"Long linear routes (long trails, river stretches, highways, etc.) unless "
"they are part of a single administrative unit (e.g., Buffalo National River "
"is a single national park) "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:18
msgid "Large cities (small towns under 7 sq mi / 20 sq km are OK)  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:20
msgid ""
"Many isolated or non-contiguous properties, even if under the same managing "
"organization."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Can hotspot groups cross administrative boundaries?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:24
msgid ""
"Yes! See our guidance for [Hotspot Groups that cross administrative "
"boundaries](Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd) below. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: GroupsIntroduction.qmd:25
msgid ""
"When a hotspot group crosses county/state/district/province lines, we "
"recommend creating a “regional” hotspot on each side of the border. Include "
"the respective administrative area in parentheses at the end of the hotspot "
"name—e.g., “Blue Lake (Lewis Co.)” and “Blue Lake (Cowlitz Co.)”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ParentHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Parent Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Every Hotspot Group MUST have a **Parent Hotspot**: a location that "
"represents the entire area. The parent location’s Hotspot page serves as an "
"overview for the whole group."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspots.qmd:5
msgid "![](images/paste-14.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ParentHotspotContent.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Parent Hotspot Content**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ParentHotspotContent.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "**About Sections**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspotContent.qmd:6
msgid ""
"An excerpt of the parent location's About content appears on each sub-"
"hotspot page. Use the About sections on the parent hotspot to describe "
"information that applies to every hotspot in the group, such as hours, fees, "
"and stewardship details."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspotContent.qmd:8
msgid "![](images/paste-15.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ParentHotspotContent.qmd:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Features**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspotContent.qmd:11
msgid ""
"Features are unique to each individual hotspot. Use the Parent hotspot's "
"Features to indicate things that are generally true for the entire area. For "
"example, if at least one hotspot in the group has a public bathroom, select "
"'Yes' for Restrooms on the Parent hotspot. Then select ‘Yes’ or ‘No’ on "
"individual sub-hotspots based on whether that specific site has a bathroom."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Additional Parent Hotspot UI**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Group Map**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:6
msgid ""
"When you visit the Parent hotspot page (the group overview page), you will "
"see a map of all hotspots in the group. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:8
msgid "![](images/paste-16.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:10
msgid "![](images/paste-18.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Hotspot Standings**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:14
msgid ""
"Each parent hotspot has a 'Hotspots' page that lists all hotspots within "
"that group, ranked by number of checklists and species—similar to the "
"Hotspot and Subregion rankings found on eBird Region pages. The checklist "
"and species totals for the parent hotspot are displayed separately at the "
"bottom of the page. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalParentHotspotUI.qmd:15
msgid "![](images/paste-19.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: DataAggregation.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Data Aggregation**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DataAggregation.qmd:4
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Parent locations aggregate data across all hotspots in the group.** Statistics for a parent location represent the entire group's combined data, including public checklists submitted to the parent.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DataAggregation.qmd:6
msgid ""
"The parent hotspot page functions as the group overview, summarizing "
"checklist submission across all hotspots in the group. Likewise, the "
"leaderboard shows top contributors based on combined activity across all "
"hotspots."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DataAggregation.qmd:8
msgid ""
"This aggregation encourages greater location precision. You can now submit "
"separate checklists to each hotspot and still have your activity count "
"toward the cumulative Top 100 for the entire area."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DataAggregation.qmd:10
msgid ""
"This technical framework may also allow us to eventually aggregate personal "
"locations into hotspot summaries in the future (but not any time soon)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DataAggregation.qmd:11
msgid ""
"Note on Bar Charts: Bar Charts for the parent location will display "
"aggregated frequency data, histograms, and chart data for the entire group. "
"To obtain Bar Chart data for the parent hotspot ONLY, add "
"&aggregateHotspots=false to the end of the Bar Chart web address."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ParentHotspotPlacement.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Parent Hotspot Placement**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspotPlacement.qmd:4
msgid ""
"We recommend placing the Parent hotspot at a central location away from more "
"precisely placed hotspots. This helps to reduce site selection confusion and "
"ensures eBird Mobile's \"Recommended Location\" algorithm only suggests the "
"parent hotspot when a GPS track spans multiple sub-hotspots or covers the "
"broader area. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspotPlacement.qmd:6
msgid ""
"If the group includes two or more regions (counties, states/provinces, or "
"countries) place the Parent hotspot in the region with the most group "
"hotspots and checklist activity. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ParentHotspotPlacement.qmd:7
msgid "See also: [Plotting Hotspots](PlottingHotspots.qmd)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: NamingParentandSub-Hotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Naming Parent Hotspots and Sub-hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NamingParentandSub-Hotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Follow [Hotspot Naming policies](index.qmd). Parent locations should have "
"“general” or “general area” in the name if there could be confusion between "
"a precise site and the overarching area. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NamingParentandSub-Hotspots.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Sub-hotspots do not HAVE to include the parent location in the name. In "
"other words, you can form Hotspots groups where sub-hotspots follow mixed "
"naming practices, some with the parent location in the name and some "
"without. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NamingParentandSub-Hotspots.qmd:8
msgid ""
"Sub-hotspots SHOULD have the parent location at the beginning of their name, "
"followed by double-dash (--) and the sub-hotspot descriptor unless the sub-"
"hotspot is an obvious and well-known standalone location. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NamingParentandSub-Hotspots.qmd:10
msgid ""
"Including the parent location in the subhotspot name is helpful to ensure "
"hotspots from the same area are grouped together in dropdown lists and "
"search results."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: NamingParentandSub-Hotspots.qmd:11
msgid "![](images/paste-24.png){fig-align=\"center\"}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**List-building Parent Hotspots (Very Large Areas)**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"In Hotspot Groups, the Parent hotspot represents the entire area covered by "
"the group. However, some areas are so large that the Parent hotspot carries "
"too much spatial uncertainty to be useful for scientific analyses. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd:6
msgid ""
"For example, Yellowstone National Park covers 13,000 square miles (33,670 "
"square km) and spans four US states. Any checklist assigned to the "
"\"Yellowstone National Park (general area)\" hotspot lacks the spatial "
"precision needed for eBird Status and Trends models."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd:8
msgid ""
"Currently, when a traveling checklist covers a distance of 50 mi (80 km) or "
"more, we automatically mark it Not Public. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd:10
#, no-wrap
msgid "**When the area within the bounding box of the group covers 80 km2 or more…**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd:12
msgid ""
"The Parent hotspot will not appear as a Recommended Location for eBird "
"Mobile checklists and cannot be selected from the map when submitting eBird "
"Mobile checklists (the parent location will still appear on eBird Mobile "
"Explore). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd:13
msgid ""
"We recommend marking any checklist submitted to a List-building Parent "
"hotspot ‘Not Public’ with the reason “Checklist-List Building”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Creating and Managing Hotspot Groups**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:4
msgid "Only eBird Hotspot Editors can create and manage Hotspot groups. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:5
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Create a Hotspot Group**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:8
msgid "Navigate to the hotspot you want to act as the parent location"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    1.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:10
msgid ""
"From the Hotspot map: Locate and tap the appropriate Hotspot pin, then click "
"the **Edit** link (upper right corner)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    2.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:12
msgid ""
"From an individual Hotspot page: Tap **Admin** from the navigation sidebar"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:14
msgid "Tap **Manage Sub-hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:16
msgid ""
"Locate nearby hotspots on the map or use the search bar to look them up by "
"name (another good reason to have the parent location in all sub-hotspot "
"names!) "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:18
msgid ""
"Once a pin is selected on the map, tap the **Add** button to add that "
"hotspot to the group"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:20
msgid ""
"Tap the **Remove** button on the Sub-hotspots list to remove a hotspot from "
"the group"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    1.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:22
msgid ""
"You can also tap a pin on the map and, if it is already part of the group, "
"tap Remove to remove it. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:24
msgid "IMPORTANT: Tap the **Save Sub-hotspots** button to save your changes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:26
msgid "![](images/paste-20.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Dissolve a Hotspot Group**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:30
msgid ""
"Follow steps 1 and 2 from **Create a Hotspot Group** (above) to access the "
"**Manage Sub-hotspots** tab on the Parent Hotspot’s Adminpage. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:32
msgid "Tap **Remove** next to each sub-hotspot in the Sub-hotspots list"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3.  '
#: CreatingandManaging.qmd:33
msgid ""
"Once all sub-hotspots are removed, the hotspot will no longer function as a "
"parent location and the group will effectively no longer exist"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Multi-Region Hotspot Groups**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Can a Hotspot Group Include Locations from Multiple Regions?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Yes! Hotspot groups can cross geopolitical boundaries. This does not mean an "
"individual checklist will appear in multiple counties. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:7
#, no-wrap
msgid "**What is the Expected Behavior When a Group Spans Multiple Regions?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:10
msgid ""
"Parent hotspots display checklist activity from all sub-locations in the "
"group. If the group covers multiple regions, data from multiple counties "
"could appear on the parent hotspot page. This does NOT feed into greater "
"county, state/province, or country-level data. Each hotspot counts toward "
"only one county, one state/province, and one country's birding activity. "
"Individual hotspots only contribute data to the regions where they are "
"located."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:12
msgid "![](images/paste-21.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:14
msgid ""
"In the example Hotspot Group above, only checklists submitted to hotspots in "
"Region A or submitted directly to the parent location will appear in Region "
"A stats. Checklists from hotspots in Region B will also appear on the parent "
"location page, but only count towards Region B stats. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:15
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Should a Hotspot Group Include Locations from Multiple Regions?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:18
msgid ""
"We understand that reviewers may hesitate to create groups where the parent "
"hotspot aggregates data from multiple regions, as it could inadvertently "
"lead to data from one county being submitted to a parent location in another "
"county. If you have concerns about this, please see our guidance below. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Large Areas**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:22
msgid ""
"For hotspot groups that cross borders because they cover large areas (e.g., "
"national parks, wildlife refuges), we are implementing a special “large area "
"process”: any hotspot group with a bounding area greater than 80km2 will be "
"designated a [List Building Location](List-buildingParentHotspots.qmd) (see "
"above). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Small Areas**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:26
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hotspot groups \\<80km2 can still span multiple geopolitical regions. Common examples include bridges or dams that cross borders along rivers. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:28
msgid ""
"When the same habitats exist on both sides of a geopolitical border (e.g., a "
"road or arbitrary line cutting through a forest), the birds found on either "
"side should be very similar—it would be hard to tell from a single checklist "
"which side of the border the observer was on if you didn’t know the exact "
"location. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:30
msgid ""
"Conversely, when geopolitical boundaries follow strong ecological boundaries "
"(e.g., Pima and Santa Cruz counties in Madera Canyon) the species lists of "
"two hotspots just across the border from each other might be dramatically "
"different—it’s easy to tell which side a checklist came from. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:32
msgid ""
"When people submit checklists directly to the parent hotspot of a group, "
"their observations will “roll up” into the county, state/province, and "
"country where the parent hotspot is located. (Note: it is almost never best "
"practice to submit to a parent hotspot, since finer-scale locations are "
"always preferable)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:34
msgid ""
"So, if the main goal is maintaining accurate **regional** data, the key "
"question is: will creating a Hotspot Group (under 80km²) clearly disrupt "
"regional data where the parent hotspot is located? "
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Consider these questions:**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:38
msgid "Do most birds cross freely from one side of the border to the other?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:40
msgid ""
"Could you tell which side of the border a checklist was from simply by "
"looking at the species list and counts? "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:42
msgid ""
"Do the habitat conditions found on one side also exist in the other county, "
"and vice versa?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:44
msgid ""
"Are species lists, high counts, and arrival/departure dates generally "
"similar on each side of the border?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Multi-RegionHotspotGroups.qmd:45
msgid ""
"If you answered \"Yes\" to these questions—assuming all other [hotspot group "
"criteria](Overview.qmd) are met—then a multi-region hotspot group shouldn’t "
"cause meaningful regional data problems. (Very long traveling checklists can "
"still cause regional data problems, so continue to be vigilant for those!)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: HotspotGroupFAQs.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Hotspot Group FAQs**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: HotspotGroupFAQs.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "**What do Hotspot Groups look like in the eBird Basic Dataset (EBD)?**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotGroupFAQs.qmd:6
msgid ""
"The eBird Basic Dataset (EBD) and Sampling Event Dataset (SED) provide data "
"at the observation and checklist level, respectively. Because each checklist "
"is associated with one specific location, Hotspot groups don’t affect how "
"data appears in the EBD and SED. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotGroupFAQs.qmd:8
msgid ""
"The location information you'll see depends on where the checklist was "
"submitted:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: HotspotGroupFAQs.qmd:10
msgid ""
"**Checklist submitted to parent hotspot:** The 'LOCALITY' and 'LOCALITY ID' "
"fields show the parent hotspot name and ID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: HotspotGroupFAQs.qmd:11
msgid ""
"**Checklist submitted to sub-hotspot in group:** The 'LOCALITY' and "
"'LOCALITY ID' fields show only that specific sub-hotspot—no parent or group "
"information is included"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Capitalization.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Capitalization**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Capitalization.qmd:3
msgid ""
"When in doubt, follow the grammar rules of the local language. In English, "
"eBird hotspots can be considered proper names and should generally be "
"capitalized, including all adjectives, common nouns, and the definite "
"article. Most formal geographic names have two parts, denoting the specific "
"and the generic (e.g., [Amherst Marsh](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1247416)). "
"The generic part (“Marsh”, in this example) tells the kind of place, "
"feature, or area to which the name refers, and the specific part (“Amherst”) "
"uniquely identifies the particular place, feature, or area.  Exceptions "
"include articles and prepositions (e.g., Alto de la Cruz, Lake of the "
"Ozarks, Fond du Lac) and phrases that give relative geographic reference  "
"(e.g., [Enders Reservoir--below dam](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1476616), "
"[Dartmoor NP--east of Tavistock](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1148230).)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Language.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Language**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Language.qmd:4
msgid ""
"eBird is a global project and we recommend that site names be listed in the "
"local language (e.g., Spanish for Central America, Portuguese for Portugal, "
"French for France and Quebec, German for Germany, etc.). These names also "
"should generally match the names used on maps and in local signage. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Language.qmd:6
msgid ""
"However, when the local language uses an alphabet that is not easily read by "
"English-speakers (or other Germanic/Romance languages), please list the site "
"name in the local language first, followed by an English translation in "
"parentheses. See examples below:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Language.qmd:8
msgid ""
"**Taiwan:** 宜蘭--頂寮生態公園 (Yilan--Dingliao Ecological Park) <http://"
"ebird.org/ebird/hotspot/L3291680>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: Language.qmd:10
msgid ""
"**Japan:** 大田区--東京港野鳥公園 (Ota Ward--Tokyo Port Wild Bird Park) "
"<http://ebird.org/ebird/hotspot/L927941>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Language.qmd:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Please use accents in non-English words in accordance with correct spelling in the original language (e.g., Río Guadalupe, Parque San José, Cañon San Pedro). Please DO NOT use accents over capital letters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: HotspotDefinitions.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Hotspot Definitions and Hierarchy**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotDefinitions.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Most hotspots are discrete, continuous sites that accurately represent a "
"geographical region—often defined by land ownership or conservation status. "
"Typical hotspots can also be thought of as representing birder behavior "
"within those properties, including a walking or driving path (i.e., track) "
"and typical strategies for looking for birds. One could theoretically draw a "
"boundary to represent any hotspot (this functionality might be added to "
"eBird in the future to more formally define these areas)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotDefinitions.qmd:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Most hotspots should be coverable in a discrete birding event**, most typically either 1) stationary count at a certain vantage point (e.g., [Shaumta Raptor Watchpoint](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L6314444)); 2) a traveling count described by a long (e.g., [Reserva Ecológica Costanera Sur](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L472208)) or short (e.g., [Brooklyn Bridge Park](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1902982)) linear, out-and-back, looped, or meandering walking route; 3) or a traveling count involving short legs by car, bike, or foot that is broken up by stops at key locations or vantage points, such as along a wildlife drive (e.g., [Edwin B. Forsythe NWR--Wildlife Drive](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L92448) or [Carretero Satipo](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L2305198)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotDefinitions.qmd:8
msgid ""
"Many hotspots represent a single, discrete, stand-alone site. However, in "
"some cases there are many hotspots in a small area, and within those areas "
"there may be discrete hierarchy of hotspots that may include a parent "
"hotspot, several sub-hotspots, and occasionally an overarching “grandparent” "
"hotspot (see [Hotspot Groups](Part3.qmd))"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotDefinitions.qmd:10
msgid ""
"As a general rule, Hotspot Groups should contain sites that are all part of "
"the same management unit, such as a state park, a national wildlife refuge, "
"or a city park. A hierarchical naming structure can also be used even when "
"sites are not part of an “official” Hotspot Group, such as along "
"particularly good sections of birding roads, rivers, or trails (see [Linear "
"Routes](LinearRoutes.qmd) below). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotDefinitions.qmd:12
msgid "![](images/paste-22.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotDefinitions.qmd:13
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Fig. 1.** Cape May Point area, showing the large number of hotspots (red, orange, yellow, and blue pins) south of the Cape May Canal, which runs through the middle of this image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Hotspot Naming—Groups**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Parent hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:6
msgid ""
"The parent hotspot should be named for the area that encompasses the entire "
"group. “General” or “general area” may be appended to the Parent hotspot "
"name if there is the potential for confusion between the parent hotspot "
"(referring to checklists spanning multiple sites or the entire area) and any "
"specific, individual sub-hotspot."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:8
msgid ""
"Any modifiers or warnings that are specific to the parent location alone "
"(e.g., “Use more precise location”) should be added in parentheses."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "**List-building Parent Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:12
#, no-wrap
msgid "List-building parent hotspots represent very large areas that are too spatially imprecise to be useful for most scientific analyses. In Hotspot Groups, List-building parent hotspots are automatically identified for any group with a bounding perimeter area of \\>80km2.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:14
msgid ""
"For very large list-building hotspots, we recommend including a "
"parenthetical note that discourages casual or regular use of these Hotspots "
"and encourages more specific birding—e.g., “(use more precise loc.)”—"
"whenever there is space to use it. Our recommendation is to keep this as "
"short and direct as possible. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:16
#, no-wrap
msgid " Any list-building parent hotspot that is considered problematic for data entry should include an asterisk after the core part of the name. An asterisk following the name is also meant to be a warning to savvy eBirders not to pick this spot if they are willing and able to submit their checklist at a more precise location. The asterisk may also help to ensure that scientific data users don’t treat these as site-specific checklists. **We ask that asterisks not be used anywhere else in hotspots so that they can be specifically used to designate these special types of locations.** \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:18
msgid "The below hotspots use our recommended names:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:20
msgid ""
"[Glacier NP\\* general (use more precise loc.)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L247319)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:22
msgid ""
"[Khao Yai NP\\* general (use more precise loc.)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L921126)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:24
msgid ""
"[Maasai Mara NR\\* general (use more precise loc.)](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L1235762)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:26
msgid ""
"[Cerro Punta\\* general area (use more precise loc.)](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L454648)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:28
msgid ""
"[Akatau Mountains\\* general area (use more precise loc.)](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L10236131)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Sub-hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:34
msgid ""
"Sub-hotspots should follow the parent hotspot separated by a **double hyphen "
"(\\-\\-) without spaces** on either side. The correct structure is: \\"
"[Parent Hotspot\\]\\-\\-\\[sub-hotspot\\]. For example, “Montezuma NWR\\-\\-"
"Towpath Rd.”\\ \\ The following variations are INCORRECT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:36
msgid "Spaces on either side of the dashes: “Montezuma NWR \\-\\- Towpath Rd.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:38
msgid "Single dash: “Montezuma NWR-Towpath Rd.” "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:40
msgid ""
"Emdash: Montezuma NWR—Towpath Rd.” (A common autocorrect change to watch out "
"for!)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:42
#, no-wrap
msgid "**NOTE:** **Using the correct structure here has been critically important since 2021, since this naming structure is used in eBird Mobile to recommend specific hotspots to the user.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:44 AdditionalModifiers.qmd:16
#: RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd:8 HistoricalLocations.qmd:6
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:22 PelagicHotspots.qmd:8 PelagicHotspots.qmd:16
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:46
msgid ""
"[Khao Yai NP\\-\\-headquarters vicinity](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L10183154)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:48
msgid "[Khao Yai NP\\-\\-Nong Phak Chi](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1080440)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:50
msgid "[Yosemite NP\\-\\-Tuolumne Meadows](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L343236)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:52
msgid "[Yosemite NP\\-\\-Glacier Pt.](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L595393)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:54
msgid ""
"[Reserva de la Biosfera El Cielo\\-\\-Senda Alta Cima](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L1332522)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:56
msgid ""
"[Reserva de la Biosfera El Cielo\\-\\-Rancho del Cielo](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L275916)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:58
msgid ""
"Do not make a city or town a parent hotspot with sub-hotspots. When it is "
"helpful to identify a location by city or town, please use this format: \\"
"[Location\\], \\[City or Town Name\\]. Furthermore, large cities do not ever "
"need to be specified in the location name (except when two hotspots with the "
"same name might be confused). For example, “Garden of the Gods Park, "
"Colorado Springs” is undesirable; it should be named “Garden of the Gods "
"Park” and the mapped location will indicate where it is more specifically. "
"If a city, town, or township is used with a road name it should generally "
"follow the road name. For instance, \"[Butler Rd., Olmito](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L2240586)\" rather than \"Olmito\\-\\-Butler Rd.\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:60
msgid ""
"Entire “Birding Trails”, covering a large section of a state, should never "
"have sub-hotspots. In the great majority of birding trails, each site or "
"stop on a birding trail should have its own location, either as a hotspot or "
"a sub-hotspots within another entity. It is permissible to have a birding "
"trail site number in parentheses after the name, for example, [Laguna "
"Atascosa NWR (LTC 024)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L129005)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Abbreviations**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HotspotNaming-Groups.qmd:63
msgid ""
"In cases where the parent location name is long, abbreviations can be "
"established for sub-hotspots, provided the parent hotspot uses the full, "
"unabbreviated version. For example, in Figure 2 above, Cape Island\\-\\-"
"SCMM\\-\\-Cove Pool is allowed because SCMM is defined (as South Cape May "
"Meadows) in the nearby parent hotspot."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Naming Hotspots along Linear Routes– Rivers, Roads, and Trails**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:4
msgid ""
"This section refers to linear features that are too long to be represented "
"by a single hotspot except for historical records and getting personal life "
"lists up to date)  This would not apply to linear features within discrete, "
"non-linear hotspots, such as trails within parks. It also does not apply to "
"pelagic transects (see the [Pelagic Hotspot](PelagicHotspots.qmd) section "
"below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Linear routes (e.g., rivers, roads, and hiking trails)—while not eligible to "
"be Hotspot groups—can still consist of a hierarchy of both stationary and "
"point-to-point “sub-hotspots” (term used loosely, not in the technical sense "
"of a Hotspot group) that follow a hierarchical naming structure. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:8
msgid ""
"One example of a linear route  consisting of multiple “sub-hotspots” is  the "
"Alaska Highway: [Alaska Hwy--Yukon River bridge to M'Clintock Bay](https://"
"ebird.org/hotspot/L6452195) (point-to-point hotspot) and [Alaska Hwy--"
"Drury's Farm pond](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L5768400) (stationary hotspot). "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:10
msgid ""
"For point-to-point sub-hotspots, the naming convention is \\[Parent "
"Hospot\\]--\\[Point A\\] to \\[Point B\\]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:12
msgid ""
"[Buffalo National River--Tyler Bend to Gilbert](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L1269187)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:14
msgid ""
"[Alakai Swamp Trail--Trailhead to Pihea Trail Junction](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L1426322)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:16
msgid ""
"[Carretera 175/Oaxaca-Tuxtepec--Km 90-95](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L282531)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: LinearRoutes.qmd:17
msgid ""
"Place the marker roughly equidistant between the two points. Not every "
"stretch of linear hotspot may qualify as a sub-hotspot. Use your judgment "
"and consider habitats and the history of how a given stretch has been birded."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: BirdingTrails.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Birding Trails**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: BirdingTrails.qmd:3
msgid ""
"Entire “Birding Trails”—multiple sites across a large region not all along "
"the same road—should never be grouped or have sub-hotspots. In the great "
"majority of birding trails, each site or stop on a birding trail should have "
"its own location, either as a standalone hotspot or a sub-hotspot within a "
"local group."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Additional Modifiers**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Occasionally, a hotspot name will need an additional modifier to clarify the "
"location. The most common situations are lakes and roads that cross county, "
"department, state, province, or even country borders (as shown in the "
"examples below) or common place names that may appear more than once in a "
"state or province (e.g., there may be more than one Blue Lake). Such "
"modifiers should follow the parent hotspot name and the sub-hotspot name (if "
"present), can use “Co.” to abbreviate County, and should always appear in "
"parentheses. **These modifiers should be used sparingly.**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:6 Towns.qmd:6 BirdcamHotspots.qmd:6
msgid "Examples: "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:8
msgid ""
"[Black Butte Lake (Glenn Co.)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L372996) and [Black "
"Butte Lake (Tehama Co.)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L515160)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:10
msgid ""
"[Boca Chica Beach (LTC 043)--USA side](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L128923) "
"and [Boca Chica (Tamaulipas)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L513174)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:12
msgid ""
"[Balsas--Rio Marañon (Dept. Amazonas)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L2237785) "
"and [Balsas--Rio Marañón (Dept. Cajamarca)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L2237773)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:14
msgid ""
"Other modifiers may sometimes be useful to clarify a location, such as the "
"town, especially when there are confusingly similar names. We generally "
"recommend using a comma to add the name of the town."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:18
msgid "[Nauset Light Beach, Eastham](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L481406)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:20
msgid "[Nauset Beach, Orleans](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L805337)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:22
msgid ""
"Hotspots that cover properties managed by land trusts and other land "
"preservation agencies may have specific organizational attribution by adding "
"the name or acronym in parentheses after the name of the property, for "
"example [Crooked Creek Preserve (TNC)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L254272) "
"for a property named Crooked Creek Preserve that is managed by The Nature "
"Conservancy. Since the names of Land Trusts can be quite long, we generally "
"recommend using these abbreviations rather than the full name of the Land "
"Trust. Although the meaning here may not be immediately obvious to all "
"users, it often is meaningful locally and is something that anyone can look "
"up on a search engine."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: AdditionalModifiers.qmd:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "**We do not ever recommend using latitude and longitude in the hotspot name;** the coordinates of a hotspot are always officially defined by where the hotspot is sited and all hotspots in eBird are associated with a specific latitude and longitude. Adding these to the name is unnecessary and likely would lead to errors if the hotspot ever were moved but the name not also adjusted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: Towns.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Towns**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Towns.qmd:4
msgid ""
"In addition, in some parts of the world (e.g., western USA) it is common to "
"go birding in small towns because the trees around town provide oasis-like "
"habitat for migrants and vagrants. In these cases, please add “town” "
"English), “pueblo” (Spanish), or an equivalent in parentheses after the "
"hotspot name so that it is clear that the hotspot refers to birding in town. "
"Do not do this for larger cities and towns, since this is intended only when "
"a town area is fairly small and is typically covered by birding the semi-"
"urban or suburban area on foot as a discrete habitat. (Despite the guidance "
"above, in some cases, sub-hotspots would be appropriate when considering the "
"town as an appropriately-sized parent hotspot.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: Towns.qmd:8
msgid "[Campo (town)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L268896)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: Towns.qmd:10
msgid "[Punta Banda (pueblo)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L234680)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: Towns.qmd:11
msgid "[Rossport (town site)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1393489)"
msgstr ""

