#. type: Title ##
#: OtherAbbreviations.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Other Abbreviations**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: OtherAbbreviations.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Other abbreviations, especially in non-English languages, can be adopted by "
"local hotspot teams. However, these need to be readily understood by the "
"eBirding community and also need to be used consistently within the region "
"and (ideally) outside of it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: OtherAbbreviations.qmd:6
msgid ""
"In general, use “and” instead of an ampersand (&) except in cases where "
"hotspot names are very long, or where ampersands are already widely used "
"(e.g., [C&O Canal--Violette’s Lock](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L192824))."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: OtherAbbreviations.qmd:8
msgid ""
"It is acceptable to use internationally recognized region abbreviations "
"(which appear in URLs in eBird, such as <https://ebird.org/region/MX-CHP>) "
"for countries, states, or provinces. Please use other abbreviations very "
"sparingly. Please be careful when using abbreviations that can be confused "
"with internationally recognized postal abbreviations—e.g., CA (California), "
"NA (Namibia), NM (New Mexico), and WA (Washington) are confusing exceptions "
"given the other abbreviations we allow."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: OtherAbbreviations.qmd:9
msgid ""
"Do not abbreviate the full name of a national park or wildlife area (For "
"example, please use Rocky Mountain NP, not RMNP). When in doubt, spell it "
"out."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Restricted Access Locations**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Although hotspots should generally be accessible to the public, occasional "
"locations are not open to the public but may be regularly birded by those "
"who have been authorized to do so. It is still appropriate to list the "
"location as a hotspot since it is desirable to pool the data from multiple "
"observers. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd:6
msgid ""
"Be sure to indicate a hotspot is Restricted Access in the [Hotspot Features]"
"(ParentHotspotContent.qmd#features) list. This will ensure that a "
"“Restricted Access” tag also appears next to the hotspot name on the eBird "
"website. Until a similar UI tag is available in eBird mobile, we recommend "
"also placing  the words “restricted access” (or the equivalent in the local "
"language) in lower-case in parentheses following the location name. Detailed "
"access instructions should not be part of the hotspot name; provide these in "
"the Plan Your Visit section of the Hotspot about page."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd:10
msgid ""
"[Patuxent River Naval Air Station (restricted access)](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L472729)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd:12
msgid ""
"[Holme Bird Observatory (restricted access)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L2038242)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: RestrictedAccessLocations.qmd:13
msgid ""
"[Finca Tempixque (acceso restringido)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L468452)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: HistoricalLocations.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Historical Locations**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: HistoricalLocations.qmd:4
msgid ""
"In rare cases, it can be helpful to create hotspots for sites that no longer "
"exist. In such cases, a parenthetical note should make it clear that the "
"described location is historical. If applicable, it may be helpful to add "
"“before YYYY” in the parenthetical to indicate the time period that the site "
"existed as a hotspot."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: HistoricalLocations.qmd:8
msgid ""
"[Al Ain Camel Racetrack (historical)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L2472490)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: HistoricalLocations.qmd:9
msgid "[Luckett Rd. pond (historical)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L3459840)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Stakeout Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"A single out-of-range rarity often generates a large amount of attention "
"from birders. When such a bird occurs at a new site (i.e., not at an already-"
"established hotspot) it is good practice to quickly set up a “stakeout” "
"hotspot to give eBirders an accurate and consistent location to use when "
"they visit. Please encourage those who “chase” these rarities to use the "
"hotspot rather than creating their own location. These hotspots should be "
"retained even after the bird has departed so that new eBird users can enter "
"past rarities."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:6
msgid "Our conventions for “stakeout hotspots” are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:8
msgid ""
"Plot the point as precisely as possible in relation to where the rarity is "
"being seen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:10
msgid "Always begin with “stakeout” in **lowercase** "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:12
msgid "Next, include the common name of the bird in the local language"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:14
msgid ""
"Next, include a geographical identifier; this can be the town, a well-known "
"road, or other feature that will distinguish this hotspot from others for "
"the same species in the region. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:16
msgid ""
"Do not include county, state, or country, since these are automatically "
"added by eBird. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:18
msgid ""
"Finally, include the date range when the bird was seen; for ongoing "
"rarities, these names may need to be edited in real time if the rare bird "
"persists for months or years"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:20
#, no-wrap
msgid "<!-- -->\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:24
msgid ""
"[stakeout Black-throated Gray Warbler, 103 James H. Luther Dr., Taunton (Jan "
"2013)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L1878310)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:26
msgid ""
"[stakeout Black-throated Sparrow, Elora (2005-06)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/"
"L1890097)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: StakeoutHotspots.qmd:27
msgid ""
"[stakeout Eurasian Blackcap, Durbanville (Jul 2017)](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L6096764)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Pelagic Hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"It is not encouraged to use hotspots for pelagic birding, since the eBird "
"best practice is to follow the [eBird Pelagic Protocol](https://"
"support.ebird.org/en/support/solutions/articles/48000950859-guide-to-ebird-"
"protocols#anchorPelagic) and plot locations based on the exact route you "
"traveled, ideally using tracks in eBird mobile. But there are two scenarios "
"where hotspots have been established and these can be useful for aggregating "
"data, especially when the data were not collected with rigorous tracks of "
"GPS location services."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:6
msgid ""
"General pelagic locations: Like other list-building parent hotspots , these "
"are most useful for aggregation of historical data under a single hotspot "
"that is reasonably well sited. They should be named according to conventions "
"described above for list-building parent hotspots and should only be used "
"when established boat trips regularly visit roughly the same waters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:10
msgid ""
"[Kaikoura--offshore--Albatross Encounter pelagic (general)](https://"
"ebird.org/hotspot/L521309)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:12
msgid "[Tofino pelagic trip](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L339307)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:14
msgid ""
"Specific pelagic locations: Sometimes an underwater feature (e.g., canyon, "
"seamount, shelf, bank) or other specific habitat is a specific area that is "
"regularly targeted for pelagic birding. These can be appropriate hotspots, "
"but of course should only be used for observations in the immediate vicinity "
"of these features; since this is hard to define for a birder on a boat, "
"these hotspots should only be established with good reason and should always "
"be used with great care. Otherwise, see above for conventions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:18
msgid "[Hudson Canyon (Atlantic Ocean)](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L670979)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: PelagicHotspots.qmd:19
msgid "[Escollo Gorda](https://ebird.org/hotspot/L504177)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: PrivacyConcerns.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Privacy concerns**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: PrivacyConcerns.qmd:3
msgid ""
"On rare occasions a rarity may appear on private land but access will be "
"controlled so as to respect the wishes of the property owner. In such cases, "
"the stakeout hotspot should be plotted some distance away from the actual "
"location in a public area and ideally the name should indicate that the "
"location plot is intentionally inaccurate and that the access is restricted. "
"Ideally, once the bird of interest has departed, the hotspot can be moved to "
"the correct location."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: BirdcamHotspots.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Birdcam hotspots**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: BirdcamHotspots.qmd:4
msgid ""
"It has become increasingly popular to watch birdcams (or other remote-"
"sensing technology) and keep lists in eBird. This practice is not formally "
"endorsed by eBird (see [our policy here](https://support.ebird.org/en/"
"support/solutions/articles/48000795623-ebird-rules-and-best-practices#Why-"
"doesn't-eBird-accept-observations-of-dead,-captive,-or-remotely-sensed-"
"birds?)), but since these checklists may be treated as Public and may have "
"public records, it is preferable to use established hotspot locations when "
"this practice is being adopted by multiple people to avoid too much location "
"scatter. Please get in touch with eBird Central for approval of any such "
"hotspots. We recommend including the overarching hotspot/area name, followed "
"by a double-dash and “feedercam” or “trailcam,” to make sure these are "
"readily identifiable; the name in parentheses is the official name of the "
"camera. Please do not add the camera weblink."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: BirdcamHotspots.qmd:8
msgid ""
"[Canopy Lodge--feedercam only (Panama Fruit Feeder Cam)](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L12059671)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    -   '
#: BirdcamHotspots.qmd:9
msgid ""
"[Manitouwadge--feedercam only (Ontario FeederWatch Cam)](https://ebird.org/"
"hotspot/L2434245)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: MiscNaming.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Miscellaneous Hotspot Naming Conventions**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1.  '
#: MiscNaming.qmd:4
msgid ""
"**Keep Names Concise** – Hotspot names should be under 100 characters, with "
"shorter names always preferred. Brevity helps ensure clarity, ease of use, "
"and consistency across platforms. Opt for widely recognized place names or "
"simple descriptive terms to maintain readability whenever possible."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2.  '
#: MiscNaming.qmd:5
msgid ""
"**Avoid Emojis** – Emojis should not be included in hotspot names. This is "
"the official policy to maintain compatibility with analytical software and "
"ensure consistency across eBird’s global dataset. We recognize the value "
"visual indicators can bring, and we are actively exploring alternative ways "
"to incorporate this information without affecting data integrity."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Downloadable Hotspot file through the Hotspot API**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Downloadable and machine-readable files can be accessed from the [eBird "
"Hotspot API](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/664302/S1ENwy59?"
"version=latest#f4f59f90-854e-4ba6-8207-323a8cf0bfe0). Hotspot editors will "
"find it useful to download a CSV file of hotspots in their region. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:6
msgid ""
"To obtain a CSV file of eBird Hotspots in a region, first request an eBird "
"API key here: <https://ebird.org/data/download> (your personal API key is "
"unique to you, please do not share it!) "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:8
msgid ""
"You will also need the appropriate region code. These can be found in the "
"URLs of the Region Explorer at <https://ebird.org/explore>. For example, the "
"region code for Zimbabwe (<https://ebird.org/region/ZW>) is ZW. The region "
"code for Cork, Munster, Ireland (<https://ebird.org/region/IE-M-CK>) is IE-M-"
"CK. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:10
msgid ""
"Substitute your API key and appropriate region code for {APIKEY} and "
"{REGIONCODE} in the following web address:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:12
msgid "https://api.ebird.org/v2/ref/hotspot/{REGIONCODE}?fmt=csv&key={APIKEY}"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:14
msgid ""
"Copy and paste the web address into your browser. The result will be a "
"downloaded CSV file of all eBird Hotspots in that region. "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:16
msgid ""
"Example: If your API key was 1a2b3c4d5e and your regions of interest were "
"Zimbabwe (ZW) and Cork, Munster, Ireland (IE-M-CK), you would paste the "
"following URLs into your web browser:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:18
msgid "https://api.ebird.org/v2/ref/hotspot/ZW?fmt=csv&key=1a2b3c4d5e"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:20
msgid "https://api.ebird.org/v2/ref/hotspot/IE-M-CK?fmt=csv&key=1a2b3c4d5e"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: DownloadHotspotFile.qmd:21
msgid ""
"The eBird API can also provide a list of species seen within the last 1-30 "
"days from any hotspot, which can then be embedded on other websites. Our "
"APIs are fully documented [here](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/"
"664302/S1ENwy59?version=latest#intro), and most of these APIs are freely "
"available for non-profit use; commercial use of the Hotspot API (or any "
"other eBird APIs) is not permitted."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ViewInGoogleEarth.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "**View the Hotspot API File in Google Earth**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ViewInGoogleEarth.qmd:4
msgid ""
"Hotspot CSV files can also be converted into Google Earth (kml) files. After "
"[downloading the Hotspot CSV](DownloadHotspotFile.qmd), open the file in "
"Excel or similar software. Insert a new, empty row 1. Enter the following "
"column headings into your new row 1: "
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ViewInGoogleEarth.qmd:6
msgid "LocalityID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '-   '
#: ViewInGoogleEarth.qmd:8
msgid "Country"
msgstr ""

